<subSubSection id="C30175E2FFAEFFBDC6A45358FE1EFD26" box="[151,403,619,646]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFAEFFBDC6A45358FE1EFD26" blockId="26.[151,614,582,646]" box="[151,403,619,646]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
(
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC6AC5358FEA0FD25" box="[159,301,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 19A–F. Pseudacteon yunnanensis sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559597/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Figs. 19A–F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC70B5358FE06FD26" box="[312,395,619,646]" captionStart="FIGURES 26" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[220,1379,181,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-19@35.[203,1385,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 26A–J. Tergite VI and sternite VI of females.A–B. P. yunnanensis sp. nov.; C–D. P. calceoliformis sp. nov.; E–F. P. hexasetalis Liu et Wang; G–H. P. tianmuensis sp. nov.; I–J. P. parviflavus sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559619/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">26A–B</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30175E2FFAEFFBDC6A45381FE0FFA45" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFAEFFBDC6A45381FDE5FCFD" blockId="26.[151,1437,690,1833]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis id="B96FFA7BFFAEFFBDC6A45381FE9FFD6C" bold="true" box="[151,274,690,716]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Female. Apical seta of palpus shorter than maximum of palpus; tarsomere 5 longer than tarsomere 1; setal palisade 2/3 length of mid tibia; setulae below basal half of hind femur shorter than those of anteroventral row of outer half; tergite VI reduced to a narrow anterior strip in middle but each lateral quarter bears 3–4 short setulae in transverse row; sternite VI large both sides and thin in middle, with 3–4 long and strong setae each side; dorsum of oviscape 7–8 minute setulae each side.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFAEFFBDC6F45254FF64FB95" blockId="26.[151,1437,690,1833]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis id="B96FFA7BFFAEFFBDC6F45254FEA8FC21" bold="true" box="[199,293,871,897]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Female.</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFAEFFBDC7F45255FDFDFC21" box="[455,624,870,897]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.03" metricValueMax="1.05" metricValueMin="1.01" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="1.03" valueMax="1.05" valueMin="1.01">1.01–1.05 mm</quantity>
. Frons (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC4E35254FCB4FC21" box="[720,825,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 19A–F. Pseudacteon yunnanensis sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559597/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 19A</figureCitation>
) brown, with 16–20 setulae. Supra-antennal setae as strong as adjacent frontal setae, upper pair being higher on frons than lower fronto-orbital setae. Lower interfrontal seta directly under lower fronto-orbital seta. Second row of frontal setae slightly concave, with upper interfronal setae further each other than either is from upper fronto-orbital seta. Flagellomere 1 brown and subglobose. Palpus brownish yellow, with 6 long setae, apical one shorter than maximum of width of palpus. Labrum and labella pale yellow.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFAEFFBDC6F4550CFDBFFA91" blockId="26.[151,1437,690,1833]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
Thorax brownish yellow, but scutum and scutellum darker. Scutellum with two pairs of setae, posterior four times length of anterior. Legs brownish yellow. Ratios of lengths of fore tarsomeres about 0.77: 0.64: 0.60: 0.56: 1, with all five bearing a posterodorsal seta palisade (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC4DD55B4FCD8FB01" box="[750,853,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 19A–F. Pseudacteon yunnanensis sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559597/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 19C</figureCitation>
). Setal palisade extends 2/3 of mid tibia (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC31455B4FA1DFB01" box="[1319,1424,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 19A–F. Pseudacteon yunnanensis sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559597/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 19D</figureCitation>
). Setae below basal half of hind femur a little shorter than those of anteroventral row of outer half (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC2D55598FAC1FB65" box="[1254,1356,1195,1221]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 19A–F. Pseudacteon yunnanensis sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559597/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 19E</figureCitation>
). Wing (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC69355FCFE8BFB49" box="[160,262,1231,1257]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 19A–F. Pseudacteon yunnanensis sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559597/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 19B</figureCitation>
) length 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFAEFFBDC75455FDFD82FB49" box="[359,527,1230,1257]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.06" metricValueMax="1.07" metricValueMin="1.05" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="1.06" valueMax="1.07" valueMin="1.05">1.05–1.07 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFAEFFBDC45555FDFC80FB49" box="[614,781,1230,1257]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.35" metricValueMax="5.4" metricValueMin="5.3" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="0.535" valueMax="0.54" valueMin="0.53">0.53–0.54 mm</quantity>
, width/length 0.50. Costal index 0.37–0.38. Costal ratios 1.86: 1. Costal cilia 
<quantity id="4CE38B8CFFAEFFBDC74955C0FDB4FAAD" box="[378,569,1267,1293]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.299999999999999" metricValueMax="4.3999999999999995" metricValueMin="4.2" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" unit="mm" value="0.043" valueMax="0.044" valueMin="0.042">
<geoCoordinate id="EE2F40AEFFAEFFBDC74955C0FE34FAAD" box="[378,441,1267,1293]" degrees="0.042" direction="north" orientation="latitude" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" precision="55" value="0.042">0.042</geoCoordinate>
<geoCoordinate id="EE2F40AEFFAEFFBDC78A55C0FD8BFAAD" box="[441,518,1267,1293]" degrees="0.044" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="26" pageNumber="227" precision="55" value="-0.044">–0.044</geoCoordinate>
mm
</quantity>
long. Costa with 12 dorsal setulae. Alula with 2–3 setae. Veins brown, membrane brownish gray. Haltere brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFAEFFBDC6F45408FB5CFA61" blockId="26.[151,1437,690,1833]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
Abdominal tergites brown and tergites I–V with sparse minute setulae on posterior margins. Tergite VI (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC35C5408FF44FADA" captionStart="FIGURES 26" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[220,1379,181,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-19@35.[203,1385,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 26A–J. Tergite VI and sternite VI of females.A–B. P. yunnanensis sp. nov.; C–D. P. calceoliformis sp. nov.; E–F. P. hexasetalis Liu et Wang; G–H. P. tianmuensis sp. nov.; I–J. P. parviflavus sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559619/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 26A</figureCitation>
) reduced to a narrow anterior strip in middle but each lateral quarter bears 3–4 short setulae in transverse row. Venter pale brown. Sternite VI (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC7CC54B0FDE9FA3E" box="[511,612,1411,1438]" captionStart="FIGURES 26" captionStartId="35.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[220,1379,181,1916]" captionTargetId="figure-19@35.[203,1385,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="35" captionText="FIGURES 26A–J. Tergite VI and sternite VI of females.A–B. P. yunnanensis sp. nov.; C–D. P. calceoliformis sp. nov.; E–F. P. hexasetalis Liu et Wang; G–H. P. tianmuensis sp. nov.; I–J. P. parviflavus sp. nov. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559619" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559619/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 26B</figureCitation>
) large both sides and thin in middle, like an eye glass, with 3–4 long and strong setae each side. The dorsum of the oviscape with 7–8 minute setulae each side (
<figureCitation id="13203AECFFAEFFBDC2535494FB49FA61" box="[1120,1220,1447,1473]" captionStart="FIGURES 19" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1451,1475]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetId="figure-19@27.[151,1435,179,1425]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 19A–F. Pseudacteon yunnanensis sp. nov., female. A. head, anterior view; B. wing, dorsal view; C. fore tarsus, posterior view; D. mid tibia, posterior view; E. hind femur, anterior view; F. ovipositor, ventral view. Scale bar = 0.1mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6559597" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6559597/files/figure.png" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Fig. 19F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BA42669FFAEFFBDC6F454F8FE0FFA45" blockId="26.[151,1437,690,1833]" box="[199,386,1483,1509]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">
<emphasis id="B96FFA7BFFAEFFBDC6F454F8FE89FA45" bold="true" box="[199,260,1483,1509]" pageId="26" pageNumber="227">Male</emphasis>
. unknown.
</paragraph>
